{{Chess Opening Theory/Position|= |Parham Attack| |rd| |bd|qd|kd|bd| |rd|= |pd|pd|pd|pd| |pd|pd|pd|= | | |nd| | |nd| | |= | | | | |pd| | |ql|= | | |bl| |pl| | | |= | | | | | | | | |= |pl|pl|pl|pl| |pl|pl|pl|= |rl|nl|bl| |kl| |nl|rl|= || }} =Parham Attack= ===3... Nf6??=== White was playing for the 'Scholar's Mate' and Black has overlooked it. This normal looking developing move 3...Nf6 allows the final blow 4. Qxf7. This position is known as 'Scholar's Mate' and is not uncommonly attempted among beginners.
==Theory table== '''1. e4 e5 2. Qh5 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6'''
White only requires one move here 4. [[/4. Qxf7|Qxf7#]]
{{ChessMid}}
==References== {{reflist}} {{wikipedia|Parham Attack|Scholars Mate}} * Illustrated Chess for Children. 1960. Harvey Kidder. Publisher, Doubleday ISBN 0-385-05764-4. {{Chess Opening Theory/Footer}}

{{Chess Opening Theory/Position|= |Scholar's Mate| |rd| |bd|qd|kd|bd| |rd|= |pd|pd|pd|pd| |ql|pd|pd|= | | |nd| | |nd| | |= | | | | |pd| | | |= | | |bl| |pl| | | |= | | | | | | | | |= |pl|pl|pl|pl| |pl|pl|pl|= |rl|nl|bl| |kl| |nl|rl|= || }} ==Parham Attack/Scholar's Mate== ===4. Qxf7#=== With this move White gives checkmate, the Black King cannot take the White queen because the White Bishop on c4 can could take back and moving the Black King to e7(Ke7) still leaves the King in check. So this position is checkmate, and White has won the game.
{{ChessMid}}
==References== {{reflist}} {{wikipedia|Scholars Mate}} * Illustrated Chess for Children. 1960. Harvey Kidder. Publisher, Doubleday ISBN 0-385-05764-4. {{Chess Opening Theory/Footer}}

